# 4. Environment Configuration

Environment variables were created to avoid hardcoding values that may change between environments.

The following variables are used:

| Variable | Purpose                        |
| -------- | ------------------------------ |
| BASE_URL | Base URL of the backend server |
| token    | JWT access token               |
| hotelId  | Selected hotel identifier      |
| roomId   | Selected room identifier       |

Using environment variables allows switching between local and production servers without modifying individual requests.

---

# 5. Variable Strategy

Different variable types were explored during the project.

Environment Variables

Used for values shared across the entire environment such as:

* BASE_URL
* token

Collection Variables

Used for values shared only within the collection.

Local Variables

Temporary variables created during request execution.

Dynamic Variables

Built-in Postman variables that generate random values when needed.

Using variables significantly reduced duplicated values and simplified request maintenance.

---

# 6. Authentication (JWT Bearer)

The application uses JWT Bearer Authentication.

Authentication flow:

1. User submits login credentials.
2. The server validates the credentials.
3. A JWT access token is returned.
4. The token is stored in Postman.
5. Protected endpoints automatically use the token in the Authorization header.

Example:

```
Authorization: Bearer {{token}}
```

This approach allows authenticated requests without manually copying the token every time.

